  {{#reveal-slide}}
    <h2 class="InfoHeader">Modal Dialog</h2>
    <p class="InfoParagraph">
      A window that forces the user to interact with it before returning to the parent application
    </p>
    <div class="InfoDetail">
      <small>
        <a href="https://ux.stackexchange.com/questions/12045/what-is-a-modal-dialog-window">ux.stackexchange.com/questions/12045/what-is-a-modal-dialog-window</a>
      </small>
    </div>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      - Why define?
      - Risky business UX-wise
      - Vetoing whatever your user is currently happily doing
      - Taking them on a round trip
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

  {{#reveal-slide}}
    <h1>There and Back</h1>
    <h3>Modal User Interaction</h3>
    <ul>
      <li class="fragment">User's focus moves from one place to another... then back</li>
      <li class="fragment">
        One place in the DOM to another... then back
        <ul>
          <li class="fragment">Modal needs to be displayed on top</li>
          <li class="fragment">Modal needs to escape the bounds of its parent</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      - As user's focus moves from one place to another, we are actually taking them someplace else in the DOM
      - Must see modal above all else in ever-escalating z-index battle
      - Parents just don't understand
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

  {{#reveal-slide}}
    <h1>This Can Be Annoying</h1>
    <p>
      Users love being interrupted as much as developers love being interrupted.
    </p>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      This is all to say modal interactions can be handled poorly or elegantly
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

  {{#reveal-slide class="Shout Shout--primaryBase" data-background-transition="fade" data-background-color="#FF4081"}}
    <h2 class="Shout-quote">Ember Modal Dialog is better than 10 Super Bowls! I don't want to oversell it, judge for yourselves.</h2>
    <div class="Shout-attribution">-Homer Simpson</div>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      The Ember Modal Dialog addon provides components to implement modal dialogs throughout an Ember application using a simple, consistent pattern.
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

  {{#reveal-slide}}
    <h1 class="CodeHeader">Usage</h1>

    <h4 class='CodeHeader CodeHeader--tight'>Template</h4>
    {{#reveal-code}}
  \{{#modal-dialog}}
    I am a modal dialog
  \{{/modal-dialog}}
    {{/reveal-code}}

    <div class='fragment'>
      {{#modal-dialog renderInPlace=true container-class='emdi-Modal'}}
        I am a modal dialog
      {{/modal-dialog}}
    </div>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      - Creating a modal is as simple as adding the modal dialog component to a template in your app
      - That's it
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

  {{#reveal-slide}}
    <h1 class="InfoHeader">From the README...</h1>
    <p class="InfoParagraph">
      Unlike other modal libraries for Ember, ember-modal-dialog uses our
      <a href="https://github.com/yapplabs/ember-wormhole" target="_blank">ember-wormhole</a>
      addon to render a modal structure as a top-level DOM element for layout
      purposes while retaining its logical position in the Ember view hierarchy.
    </p>
    <div class="InfoDetail">
      <small>
        <a href="https://github.com/yapplabs/ember-modal-dialog#ember-modal-dialog--" target="_blank">
          github.com/yapplabs/ember-modal-dialog
        </a>
      </small>
    </div>

    {{#reveal-slide-notes}}
      - Takes care of DOM things
      - Uses another addon called `ember-wormhole`
      - Brags about not diverting us from the Ember view hierarchy
      - Alludes to other approaches not taken
    {{/reveal-slide-notes}}
  {{/reveal-slide}}

